1. What are the types of variables in Java?
-->In Java, variables are containers used to store data, classified by their scope and lifetime into three main types: Local (inside methods/blocks),
    Instance (non-static, inside class), and Static (shared across class instances). They hold either primitive data (int, char, boolean) or reference
    data (Objects, Arrays). 
  
    Here is a detailed breakdown of the types of variables in Java:
    1. Local Variables
    Definition: Declared inside a method, constructor, or block.
    Scope: Limited to the block, method, or constructor in which they are declared.
    Lifetime: Created upon entering the scope and destroyed upon exit.
    Initialization: Must be initialized before use, as they have no default values.
    Example: void myMethod() { int a = 10; } // 'a' is a local variable. 

    2. Instance Variables
    Definition: Declared inside a class but outside any method, constructor, or block.
    Scope: Visible to all methods, constructors, or blocks within the class.
    Lifetime: Created when an instance (object) of the class is created and destroyed when the object is destroyed.
    Default Values: Have default values (e.g., 0 for int, null for objects).
    Example: class MyClass { int instanceVar; } // 'instanceVar' belongs to the object. 
  
    3. Static (or Class) Variables
    Definition: Declared with the static keyword inside a class, outside any method.
    Scope: Global to all instances of the class; only one copy exists regardless of the number of objects created.
    Lifetime: Created when the program starts and destroyed when the program ends.
    Usage: Usually declared as public/private, final, and static.
    Example: class MyClass { static int staticVar; } // 'staticVar' is shared. 



2. Difference between instance, static, and local variables.
-->
| Feature              | Local Variable                       | Instance Variable               | Static Variable                    |
| -------------------- | ------------------------------------ | ------------------------------- | ---------------------------------- |
| **Declaration**      | Inside method, constructor, or block | Inside class, outside methods   | Inside class with `static` keyword |
| **Belongs to**       | Method/Block                         | Object                          | Class                              |
| **Scope**            | Limited to the block                 | Throughout class (via object)   | Throughout class                   |
| **Lifetime**         | Exists during method execution       | Exists as long as object exists | Exists as long as class is loaded  |
| **Memory Location**  | Stack                                | Heap                            | Method Area (Class Area)           |
| **Copies**           | New copy for each method call        | One per object                  | Single shared copy                 |
| **Access**           | Within method only                   | Using object                    | Using class or object              |
| **Default Value**    | ❌ No default (must initialize)       | ✅ Default values assigned       | ✅ Default values assigned          |
| **Keyword Required** | No                                   | No                              | Yes (`static`)                     |




3. Can we declare variables inside a method as static?
-->No, not allowed
    👉 Java does NOT allow:
    void show() {
        static int x = 10;  // ❌ Error
    }
    ✔ static is only allowed at class level



4. Scope and lifetime of instance variables, static variable, local variables?
-->
| Variable Type | Scope                     | Lifetime                         |
| ------------- | ------------------------- | -------------------------------- |
| Instance      | Entire class (via object) | Till object exists               |
| Static        | Entire class              | Till program ends (class loaded) |
| Local         | Inside method/block       | Till method execution ends       |



5. How are static variables shared among objects?
-->When you declare a variable as static, the Java Virtual Machine (JVM) creates only one copy of that variable in a special memory area called
    the Method Area or Metaspace.
    👉 Static variables are created only once
    
    class Demo {
        static int count = 0;
    }
    All objects share the same copy
    If one object changes it → all see updated value



