-->
| Variable Type | Memory Location          |
| ------------- | ------------------------ |
| Instance      | Heap (inside object)     |
| Static        | Method Area (Class Area) |
| Local         | Stack                    |


9. What is the difference between class-level and object-level variables?
-->Class-Level Variables (Static Variables)
    Definition: Declared with the static keyword inside a class but outside any method.
    Storage: Only one copy exists for the entire class, regardless of how many objects are created. They are stored in static memory
    (Metaspace/PermGen) and created when the class is loaded.
    Accessibility: Can be accessed directly using the class name (e.g., ClassName.variableName) without creating an object.
    Behavior: If one object modifies a class-level variable, the change is reflected across all other objects. 

    Object-Level Variables (Instance Variables)
    Definition: Declared without the static keyword inside a class but outside any method.
    Storage: Each object has its own unique copy of these variables. They are stored on the heap and created when an object is instantiated
    using the new keyword.
    Accessibility: Can only be accessed through a specific object reference (e.g., objectName.variableName).
    Behavior: Changes made to an object-level variable in one instance do not affect the variables in other instances.


